    <name>
				<text>37.2.3.10 A machine is built to make mass-produced items</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p><p>A machine is built to make mass-produced items. Each item made by the machine has a probability \(p\) of being defective. Given the value of \(p,\) the items are independent of each other. Because of the way in which the machines are made, \(p\) could take one of several values. In fact \(p=X/100\) where \(X\) can take any value from \(\{0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5\}\) with equal probability. The machine is tested by counting the number of items made before a defective is produced. Find the conditional probability distribution of \(X\) given that the first defective item is the number \({@n_first_def_item@}\) to be made.</p><p>Let \(Y\) be the number of the first defective item. Complete fill the following table with the correct answers <u>rounded to 4 decimal places</u>. Use additional zero(s) if your answer is exact to a lower degree of accuracy.</p>
<table class="HELM_table">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>\(j\)</th>
      <th>\(\text{P}(X=j | Y={@n_first_def_item@})\)</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>\(0\)</td>
      <td>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(1\)</td>
      <td>[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(2\)</td>
      <td>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(3\)</td>
      <td>[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(4\)</td>
      <td>[[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(5\)</td>
      <td>[[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] [[feedback:prt6]]</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table><br><br>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p><b>SOLUTION:</b></p><p>Let \(Y\) be the number of items until the first defective item, so by Bayes' rule:</p><p>\(\begin{aligned} \text{P}(X=j \mid Y={@n_first_def_item@}) &amp;= \dfrac{\text{P}(X=j)\times \text{P}(Y={@n_first_def_item@} \mid X=j)}{\sum_{i=0}^{5} \text{P}(X=i)\times \text{P}(Y={@n_first_def_item@} \mid X=i)} \\ &amp; = \dfrac{ \text{P}(Y={@n_first_def_item@} \mid X=j)}{ \sum_{i=0}^{5} \text{P}(Y={@n_first_def_item@} \mid X=i)} \end{aligned}\)</p><p>since \( \text{P}(X=j) =1/6 \) for \( j=0, \ldots , 5. \)</p><p><br></p><p><span style="font-size: 0.9375rem;">If \(Y\) is the number of items until the first defective item, then the sequence of events must be \(1\)st good, \(2\)nd good, ..., {@n_first_def_item_less1@}th good and then {@n_first_def_item@}th defective. Since the probability of defective is&nbsp;&nbsp;\( p = X/100\) and as the items are independent, it follows that:</span><br></p><p><span style="font-size: 0.9375rem;">\(\text{P}(Y={@n_first_def_item@} \mid X=j) = \left(1- \frac{j}{100} \right)^{{@n_first_def_item_less1@}} \left(\frac{j}{100} \right)&nbsp;\)</span><br></p><p>With the latter, we can fill the table as follows:</p><p><br></p>
<table class="HELM_table">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>\(j\)</th>
      <th>\(\text{P}(X=j | Y={@n_first_def_item@})\)</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>\(0\)</td>
      <td>{@ta_1@}</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(1\)</td>
      <td>{@ta_2@}</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(2\)</td>
      <td>{@ta_3@}</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(3\)</td>
      <td>{@ta_4@}</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(4\)</td>
      <td>{@ta_5@}</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>\(5\)</td>
      <td>{@ta_6@}</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
